'''Sumidagawa Shrine''' (隅田川神社) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社}} located in [[Sumida Ward]], [[Tokyo]]. The surrounding area is part of {{ill|Higashi-Shirahige Park|ja|東白鬚公園}}.

== Enshrined Deities ==
The shrine venerates the following deities:
* {{ill|Hayaakitsuhiko-no-Kami|ja|速秋津日子神}}
* {{ill|Hayaakitsuhime-no-Kami|ja|速秋津比売神}}
* {{ill|Torinoiwakusufune-no-Kami|ja|鳥之石楠船神}}
* {{ill|Ōkajikidohime-no-Kami|ja|大楫木戸姫神}}

== History ==
The founding of this shrine is unknown, but legend attributes its establishment to {{ill|Minamoto no Yoritomo|ja|源頼朝}}. Originally named '''Ukishima Shrine''', it was historically referred to by various names such as Suijin Shrine, Suijin-gū, and Ukishima-gū, and has been affectionately called "Suijin-sama." In 1872, it was renamed to its current title.

In addition to serving as the local {{ill|Chinju|ja|鎮守神}}, the shrine is considered the guardian deity of the Sumida River area. It has attracted devotion from water transportation workers, boatmen, and people working in the water trade due to its association with "water gods."

== Stone Monuments ==
The shrine grounds feature a signpost written by Edo-period {{ill|Gesaku|ja|戯作}} writer {{ill|Santō Kyōzan|ja|山東京山}} and a poetry monument dedicated to {{ill|Kadosu Manako|ja|鹿都部真顔}}, a master of {{ill|Kyōka|ja|狂歌}}.

== Access ==
* A 10-minute walk from {{ill|Kanegafuchi Station|ja|鐘ヶ淵駅}} ({{OSM map route|start=35.73337,139.81991|goal=35.73274,139.81277|name=Route Directions}}).

== Related Topics ==
{{Commonscat}}
* {{ill|Suijin Bridge|ja|水神大橋}}
* {{ill|Shirahige Bridge|ja|白鬚橋}}
* {{ill|Sumida River Ferries#Suijin no Watashi|ja|隅田川の渡し#水神の渡し}}
* {{ill|Ikarashi Shōji|ja|井狩正司}} (1916–2011, former chief priest and former professor at {{ill|Nihon University College of Humanities and Sciences|ja|日本大学文理学部}})

== External Links ==
* [http://www.tokyo-jinjacho.or.jp/syoukai/13_sumida/13014.html Sumidagawa Shrine (Tokyo Shrine Office)]

